'''Sannomiya Jinja''' (三宮神社) is a Shinto shrine located in {{ill|Sannomiya-chō (Kobe City)|de|Sannomiya-chō (Kobe City)|ja|三宮町 (神戸市)|lt=Sannomiya-chō|lt_ja=三宮町|lt_de=Sannomiya-chō|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sannomiya-chō (Kobe City)|qq=}}, {{ill|Chuo Ward (Kobe)|de|Chuo Bezirk (Kobe)|ja|中央区 (神戸市)|lt=Chuo Ward|lt_ja=中央区|lt_de=Chuo Bezirk|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chuo Ward (Kobe)|qq=}}, {{ill|Kobe|de|Kōbe|ja|神戸市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kobe|qq=}}, in {{ill|Hyōgo Prefecture|de|Hyōgo Präfektur|ja|兵庫県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hyōgo Prefecture|qq=}}. It is the third among the eight shrines collectively known as the {{ill|Ikuta Eight Sub-shrines|de|Ikuta Eight Sub-shrines|ja|生田裔神八社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ikuta Eight Sub-shrines|qq=}}, each of which enshrines one of the offspring deities of {{ill|Ikuta Shrine|de|Ikuta-Schrein|ja|生田神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ikuta Shrine|qq=}}. The chief deity of this shrine is {{ill|Takitsuhime-no-Mikoto|de|Takitsuhime-no-Mikoto|ja|湍津姫命|1=Tagitsuhime|2=ja|3=タギツヒメ|4=zh|5=多岐都比賣命|6=fr|7=Tagitsuhime|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takitsuhime-no-Mikoto|13=User:Immanuelle/Tagitsuhime|qq=}}.

This shrine also gave its name to the surrounding area known as “Sannomiya.”

== Overview ==
As a guardian of safe navigation and the prosperity of commerce and industry, this shrine has long been deeply revered by the general populace. Because no ancient records remain, the exact date of its founding is unknown. Its enshrined deity, Takitsuhime-no-Mikoto, is a goddess of water. Within the precincts stand the “Kawara Reisha,” a monument marking the historical site where the {{ill|Kobe Incident|de|Kobe-Zwischenfall|ja|神戸事件|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kobe Incident|qq=}} began, and a cannon from that era.

In the 4th year of the Keiō era (1st year of the Meiji era, 1868), a conflict broke out in front of Sannomiya Jinja between soldiers of the Okayama Domain (Bizen Domain) and foreign troops. This became the first diplomatic incident for the Meiji government, referred to as the {{ill|Kobe Incident|de|Kobe-Zwischenfall|ja|神戸事件|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kobe Incident|qq=}} or the Bizen Incident.

